  "why": "The paper uses model-internal signals (neuron coverage) and statistical patterns of discovered failures to characterize where and how failures occur (e.g., defining local/global neuron coverage, a coverage-guided fitness, reporting coverage increases and counts of erroneous / quantization-difference-inducing inputs). This constitutes partial diagnostic insight because it links failures to model internals and search behavior. However, the paper does not trace failures to underlying root causes such as dataset bias, corrupted training data, spurious features, or overfitting, nor does it present per-class or feature-level analyses that would explain why the model is vulnerable. Thus it provides internal/occurrence characterization but not explanations of underlying vulnerabilities.",
  "evidence": "Section IV.B (Page 3) – DNN Coverage: \"Local neurons coverage (NLNC): this represents the new neurons covered by the mutated test input that have not been covered by its corresponding original test input. Global neurons coverage (NGNC): this consists of the new neurons covered by the mutated test input that have not been covered by all the previous test inputs... We define the following fitness function: Fitness = α × NLNC + β × NGNC (1)\". Section V.A–V.C / RQ1–RQ2 (Pages 3-4) – coverage and failure statistics: \"DeepEvolution significantly boosts the neuronal coverage...\" (Table I) and \"DeepEvolution can effectively generate test cases that trigger erroneous behaviors of the DNN. Table II presents erroneous behaviors detected by each metaheuristic algorithm.\". Section V.C / RQ2 (Page 4) – interpretation tying failures to coverage/search: \"...the local coverage level integrated in the fitness function plays an important role in assessing how much the DNN’s state of the transformed input is different from the state that resulted from the original input.\". Absence of root-cause analysis: No sections or quotes in the paper link discovered failures to underlying model vulnerabilities such as biased/corrupted training data, spurious features, or overfitting (see entire evaluation Sections V and VI where results are reported but no causal attribution is made)."
